  "question": "Carla is downloading a 200 GB file. Normally she can download 2 GB/minute, but 40% of the way through the download, Windows forces a restart to install updates, which takes 20 minutes. Then Carla has to restart the download from the beginning. How load does it take to download the file?",
  "prompt": "Carla is downloading a 200 GB file. Normally she can download 2 GB/minute, but 40% of the way through the download, Windows forces a restart to install updates, which takes 20 minutes. Then Carla has to restart the download from the beginning. How load does it take to download the file?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "160",
  "generated_text": "To find the total time Carla takes to download the file, we need to break the process into three distinct phases:\n1.  **Initial Download**: Downloading for 40% of the time without interruption.\n2.  **Restart**: The system restarts, taking 20 minutes.\n3.  **Retry**: Downloading the remaining 60% of the file from scratch.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the time for the initial download.**\nThe total file size is 200 GB, and the normal download speed is 2 GB/minute.\n$$ \\text{Initial Time} = \\frac{\\text{File Size}}{\\text{Speed}} = \\frac{200 \\text{ GB}}{2 \\text{ GB/min}} = 100 \\text{ minutes} $$\n\n**Step 2: Determine how much of the file has been downloaded.**\nThe restart happens 40% of the way through the download.\n$$ \\text{Completed Amount} = 100 \\text{ minutes} \\times 40\\% = 100 \\times 0.4 = 40 \\text{ minutes of download} $$\n$$ \\text{Downloaded Amount} = 2 \\text{ GB/min} \\times 40 \\text{ min} = 80 \\text{ GB} $$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the time for the retry.**\nThe file size is 200 GB. She has downloaded 80 GB.\n$$ \\text{Remaining Amount} = 200 \\text{ GB} - 80 \\text{ GB} = 120 \\text{ GB} $$\nThe new download speed is the same (2 GB/minute).\n$$ \\text{Retry Time} =",
